abstract = {The growth of data available on the Web, especially through social networks and business transactions, has served as a driving force for the development of recommender systems. Although there are many techniques in the literature, these systems suffer from some problems, including the well-known cold start problem. This problem is related to the recommendations of new elements or new users when there is no initial knowledge base. In this study we propose a solution to this and other problems based on use of semantic. We present SeRenA (Semantic Recommender for All), an unsupervised recommending strategy based on extraction of initial interests through online data (eg. posted-message and friendship) and mapped onto a number of Wikipedia documents. We introduce the methods and techniques we plan to apply to discover new items over ambiguous knowledge base.},
